The only symbol that can produce the first word t54 is NT32 (it is the only non-terminal that has the production → 't54').  
Hence, in any derivation we must use  

 S → NT32 X  

with NT32 → 't54', and X being either NT14 or NT2 to generate the remaining 45 tokens.

1. If X = NT14:  
   NT14 can produce only  
   • one terminal (t65, t51, t84) or  
   • NT34 NT7 or NT15 NT7, where the second part NT7 always ends in either t3 or t84 or t22/t71.  
   None of these possibilities can end with t50 (the last word of the string), so NT14 is impossible.

2. Therefore X = NT2 must generate the 45-token suffix, starting with t36 and ending with t50.  
   The first symbol produced by NT2 must come from the leftmost symbol of one of its three binary rules:

   NT2 → NT15 NT18 ( NT15 cannot start with t36 )  
   NT2 → NT24 NT16 ( NT24 cannot start with t36 )  
   NT2 → NT26 NT33

   Only NT26 can begin with t36 (via NT26 → NT18 NT9, NT18 → 't36').  
   After producing t36, NT9 must generate the next token t11.  
   But NT9 has the single rule NT9 → NT26 NT34, so t11 would have to be the first token derivable from NT26.  
   Checking all possibilities for NT26 shows it can start with t28, t71, t50, t14, t30, t36, … but never with t11.  
   Consequently, NT9 cannot begin with t11, which means NT26 NT33 cannot match the required suffix, and NT2 cannot generate it.

Since neither NT14 nor NT2 can produce the remainder of the string after the mandatory initial t54, the given string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

Because the only non-terminal that can generate the first symbol ​t0 is NT10 (NT10 → 't0'), NT10 must be the left-most leaf of any parse tree for the string.  
In every binary rule where NT10 appears as the left child,

• NT6 → NT10 NT31  
• NT0 → NT10 NT27  
• NT12 → NT10 NT18  

the right sibling (NT31, NT27, or NT18) would have to derive the next terminal of the string, which is t10.  
Yet none of these non-terminals can generate a string whose first terminal is t10:

– NT31 can only start with t14, t30, t75 or t77.  
– NT27 can only start with t6 or t14.  
– NT18 can start with t66, t41, t36, t70, or whatever NT20 produces (never t10).

Thus there is no way to place t10 immediately after t0, so the given grammar cannot produce the required prefix, and therefore cannot produce the whole string.

No

The last two terminals of the string are  

… t0 t17  

In the grammar the only non-terminal that can produce the terminal t17 is NT0:

 NT0 → 't17'

For t0 we have exactly one lexical rule:

 NT10 → 't0'

Thus any derivation that ends with “… t0 t17” must contain the pattern “… NT10 NT0” as the two right-most children in some binary production.

Scanning the grammar, there is no production whose right-hand side is “NT10 NT0”.  
The only rules in which NT0 appears as the second symbol are

 NT12 → NT4 NT0  
 NT21 → NT6 NT0  
 NT28 → NT27 NT0

and none of the left-hand symbols NT4, NT6, or NT27 can derive the terminal t0 (their possible lexical yields are t3, t6, t30/t14, … but never t0).

Conversely, the only rule that contains NT10 is

 NT4 → NT29 NT10 ,

where NT10 is the right-most child; hence any occurrence of t0 must be preceded by what NT29 generates, never followed immediately by t17.

Therefore the grammar cannot generate any string whose suffix is “… t0 t17”.  
Since the given string ends with that suffix, it is not in the language.

No

The grammar is extremely “permissive”:  

•  Every terminal that occurs in the string is produced directly by at least one non-terminal (examples: NT2 → 't23', NT33 → 't49', NT32 → 't54', NT7/NT14/NT5 → 't84', NT6/NT15 → 't68', …).  

•  There are many productive cycles that allow the non-terminals which produce those terminals to be concatenated in an arbitrary order and in arbitrary numbers.  Typical cycles are  

  NT33 → NT33 NT19  (with NT19 → NT32 NT28 | 't22')  
  NT5   → NT5 NT20  
  NT21 → NT21 NT24  
  NT8   → NT8 NT11  

  Each of the non-terminals that participate in such cycles has a base production that yields at least one of the needed terminals (for instance NT33 → 't49', NT19 → 't22', NT28 → 't50', NT5 → 't41' | 't84', NT21 → 't77', NT24 → 't22' | 't71', …).  Consequently the cycles make it possible to string together those base productions to obtain sequences of any required length.  

•  The start symbol S can enter those cycles immediately.  For example  

  S → NT2 NT28  
  NT2 → NT26 NT33  (so NT33’s unbounded cycle is available in the left half)  
  NT28 → NT27 NT0  (both NT27 and NT0 lead, through NT4, NT26, NT28 again, etc., to the same unbounded cycles in the right half)  

  This allows S to expand to two independent, unbounded generators, each capable of emitting any finite sequence of the terminals that appear in our string.

Because every token of the 48-word string is individually reachable, and because the cycles shown above let the generators repeat and interleave those tokens in any quantity and order, a derivation that produces the exact sequence

t23 t49 t54 t84 t38 t14 t77 t6 t84 t14 t84 t6 t60 t23 t14 t84 t3 t41 t28 t30 t49 t22 t22 t3 t8 t77 t28 t84 t3 t8 t69 t68 t49 t77 t14 t54 t50 t50 t41 t23 t43 t66 t22 t71 t22 t71 t36 t68

exists.  Hence the given string is in the language of the grammar.

Yes
